{"title_page": "First Citizens BancShares", "text_new": "{{Infobox company\n| name           =  First Citizens BancShares\n| logo           = \n| logo_size      = 250px\n| type           = [[Public company|Public]]\n| traded_as      = {{NASDAQ|FCNCA}} (Class A)<br>[[Russell 1000 Index]] component\n| foundation     =  1898\n| location       = [[Raleigh, North Carolina]], [[United States]]\n| area_served    = [[Arizona]], [[California]], [[Colorado]], [[District of Columbia]], [[Florida]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], [[Kansas]], [[Maryland]], [[Minnesota]], [[Missouri]], [[New Mexico]], [[North Carolina]], [[Oklahoma]], [[Oregon]], [[Pennsylvania]], [[South Carolina]], [[Tennessee]], [[Texas]], [[Virginia]], [[Washington (state)|Washington]], [[West Virginia]], [[Wisconsin]] \n| key_people     = [[Frank B. Holding Jr.]] <small>([[Chief executive officer|CEO]]) ([[Chairman of the Board]])</small>\n| industry       = [[Finance]], [[Investments]], and [[Insurance]]\n| products       = [[Commercial bank]]ing, [[Investment bank]]ing\n| net_income     = {{augmentation}} [[U.S. dollar|US$]] 226 million (2016)\n| assets         =   {{augmentation}}[[U.S. dollar|US$]] 33 billion (2016)\n| num_employees  =  ~5,000\n| homepage       =  [http://www.firstcitizens.com/ www.firstcitizens.com]\n}}\n\n'''First Citizens Bancshares, Incorporated''' ({{nasdaq|FCNCA}}) is a [[bank holding company]] based in [[Raleigh, North Carolina]] that operates '''First Citizens Bank.'''  First Citizens operates in 18 states and the District of Columbia in the [[United States]], concentrated in the [[Southeastern United States]], [[Southern California]], and [[Washington (state)|Washington]].\n\nAssuming completion of a merger announced in June 2014, First Citizens Bank will become the sixth largest bank in the Southeast with 575 branches in 18 states and the [[District of Columbia]], $30.7 billion in assets, $26.1 billion in deposits, and $18 billion in loans.<ref name=SC/>  In 2010 the company employed approximately 4,400 employees.<ref name=\"iBank\">{{cite web\n|url=http://www.ibanknet.com/scripts/callreports/getbank.aspx?id=ibn1438&cert=1075612\n|title=Associated Banc-Corp\n|accessdate=2010-09-30\n|date=2010-09-30\n|work=Holding Companies\n|publisher=iBanknet.com\n}}</ref>\n\nFirst Citizens Bank serves clients in more than 200 locales with 571 branches in [[Arizona]], [[California]], [[Colorado]], [[District of Columbia]], [[Florida]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], [[Kansas]], [[Maryland]], [[Minnesota]], [[Missouri]], [[New Mexico]], [[North Carolina]], [[Oklahoma]], [[Oregon]], [[South Carolina]], [[Tennessee]], [[Texas]], [[Virginia]], [[Washington (state)|Washington]], [[Pennsylvania]], and [[West Virginia]].\n\n==History==\nIn 1998, First Citizens Bank made an agreement with [[First Citizens Bank of South Carolina]], also controlled by the Frank Holding family, allowing customers of either bank to conduct transactions with the other institution.<ref>\"Briefly,\" ''The News & Observer'', July 23, 1998, p. D2.</ref>\n\nDec 22, 2003, Citizens Bancshares restated its previously announced 2003 third quarter earnings, following a determination by its independent auditors to change its accounting treatment of one third quarter transaction related to shares of the Company's common stock donated to it by an unrelated third party.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/containers/fix031/813640/000110465903029082/a03-6490_1ex99d1.htm| title=Citizens Bancshares Corporation Announces Revised Third Quarter Earnings}}</ref>\n\nOn October 8, 2010, First Citizens filed a merger application with federal regulators, the [[Office of the Comptroller of the Currency]] and the [[Federal Reserve Bank of Richmond]], and respective state banking departments in IronStone's footprint. IronStone Bank will continue to operate under its trade name.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/charlotte/stories/2010/10/04/daily54.html|title=\nFirst Citizens looks to merge with IronStone Bank|last=Weisbecker|first=Lee|work=[[Charlotte Business Journal]]|date=2010-10-08|accessdate=2011-01-24}}</ref> The change became official January 7, 2011.<ref name=Ranii>{{cite news|url=http://blogs.newsobserver.com/business/first-citizens-completes-in-house-merger|title=First Citizens completes in-house merger|last=Ranii|first=David|work=[[News & Observer]]|date=2011-01-07|accessdate=2011-01-07}}</ref>\n\nFirst Citizens Bank entered into an agreement with the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. (FDIC) to purchase substantially all the assets and assume the majority of the liabilities of United Western Bank, [[Denver, Colorado]] on January 21, 2011.<ref name=United/> Months later First Citizens took over the failed Colorado Capital Bank of [[Castle Rock, Colorado]] in a similar deal. It was the sixth FDIC-related agreement since July 2009.<ref name=Langford>{{cite news|url=http://www.salisburypost.com/News/071711-biz-roundup-langford-nominee-qcd|title=Lighting company CFO finalist for honor|work=[[Salisbury Post]]|date=2011-01-21|accessdate=2011-01-24|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110924031733/http://www.salisburypost.com/News/071711-biz-roundup-langford-nominee-qcd|archivedate=2011-09-24}}</ref> First Citizens now has 14 branches in Colorado, 3 of them IronStone.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/First-Citizens-Bank-Purchases-pz-416410419.html?x=0&.v=1|title=First Citizens Bank Purchases Certain Assets, Assumes Certain Liabilities of Colorado Capital Bank|work=Yahoo Finance|date=2011-07-08|accessdate=2011-07-21}}</ref>\n\nOn December 10, 2013, 1st Financial Corp. shareholders approved a merger with First Citizens. As of September 30, 2013, [[Hendersonville, North Carolina]]-based 1st Financial had 12 branches in Western North Carolina, $675 million in assets and $660 million in deposits. In spring 2014, accounts of Mountain 1st Bank & Trust are to change to First Citizens.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.citizen-times.com/article/20131211/NEWS/312110049/Mountain-1st-First-Citizens-merger-OK-d|title=Mountain 1st-First Citizens merger OK'd|work=[[Asheville Citizen-Times]]|date=2013-12-10|accessdate=2013-12-18}}</ref>\n\nOn October 1, 2014, First Citizens completed a merger with [[First Citizens Bank of South Carolina]], making First Citizens the sixth-largest bank in the Southeast resulting in the largest bank in the United States controlled by a single family. First Citizens had no branches in South Carolina before the merger, while First Citizens and the South Carolina-based bank both had branches in Georgia.<ref name=SC>{{cite news|url=http://www.thestate.com/2014/06/11/3501235/first-citizens-bank-buys-sc-based.html|title=First Citizens Bank buys SC-based bank|last=Ranii|first=David|work=[[News & Observer]]|date=2014-06-11|accessdate=2014-06-11|archive-url=https://archive.is/20140611151752/http://www.thestate.com/2014/06/11/3501235/first-citizens-bank-buys-sc-based.html|archive-date=2014-06-11|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=First Citizens Completes Merger|work=[[Asheville Citizen-Times]]|date=2014-10-05|page=E2}}</ref>\n\nOn March 11, 2016, North Milwaukee State Bank of [[Milwaukee]], the first bank to fail in 2016, was taken over and the FDIC appointed receiver. First Citizens agreed to purchase most of the $67.1 million in assets and all of the deposits.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.newsobserver.com/news/business/article65953337.html|title=First Citizens acquires failed Wisconsin bank|last=Ranii|first=David|work=News & Observer|date=2016-03-14|accessdate=2016-05-09}}</ref>\n\nOn May 6, 2016, First Citizens announced the purchase of [[King of Prussia, Pennsylvania]]-based First CornerStone Bank, the third financial institution to fail in 2016, with six branches, $103.3 million in assets and $101 million in deposits.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.newsobserver.com/news/business/article76492917.html|title=First Citizens Bank acquires failed Pa. bank |last=Ranii|first=David|work=News & Observer|date=2016-05-09|accessdate=2016-05-09}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2016, First Citizens completed its $35 million purchase of Cordia Bancorp Inc. of [[Midlothian, Virginia]], with $353.8 million in assets.<ref name=Journal/>\n\nOn January 13, 2017, First Citizens announced it agreed to take over the failed Harvest Community Bank of [[Pennsville, New Jersey]], with $126.4 million in assets and four branches.<ref name=Journal>{{cite news|url=http://www.journalnow.com/business/business_news/local/the-briefcase-local-businessmen-offer-securities-for-sneez/article_7ab36c0d-b2ce-50b1-91da-ba8063d9de3c.html|title=The Briefcase: Local businessmen offer securities for SneeZ|work=[[Winston-Salem Journal]]|date=2017-01-16|accessdate=2017-02-02}}</ref>\n\nOn May 5, 2017, First Citizens announced it agreed to take over the failed Milwaukee-based Guaranty Bank of [[Milwaukee, Wisconsin]], with estimated $1 billion in assets.<ref name=Fox6>{{cite news|url=http://fox6now.com/2017/05/05/federal-agency-shuts-down-all-guaranty-bank-branches-will-be-absorbed-by-first-citizens-bank/|title=Federal agency shuts down number of Guaranty Bank branches; some to reopen as First-Citizens Bank|work=[[Fox 6 News]]|date=2017-05-05|accessdate=2017-05-06}}</ref>\n\n== Timeline ==\nFirst Citizens Bank, first known as the Bank of [[Smithfield, North Carolina|Smithfield]], opened on March 1, 1898. It eventually evolved into First National Bank of Smithfield, and merged with Citizens National Bank to become First and Citizens National Bank. In 1929, it changed its name to First-Citizens Bank and Trust Company.<ref name=Holding>[https://www.ncdcr.gov/blog/2015/03/01/the-holding-family-and-first-citizens-bank The Holding Family and First Citizens Bank] at [[North Carolina Department of Natural Resources.</ref> It reorganized as a holding company, First Citizens BancShares, in 1986.<ref>[https://last10k.com/sec-filings/report/798941/000079894118000006/fcnca_10kx12312017.htm 2017 Form 10-K]</ref> \n\nFor three generations, the bank has been led by the family of Robert Powell Holding, who joined the bank in 1918 and rose to president in 1935.<ref name=Holding/>\n\n* 1971 \u2013 acquired The Haynes Bank of Cliffside, North Carolina<ref name=\"FDIC-FCB\">{{cite web\n|url=http://www2.fdic.gov/idasp/report_bhc.asp?inSortIndex=0&inCert1=1075612&period1=06/30/2006\n|title=Bank Holding Company Detail\n|accessdate=2007-04-15\n|date=2006-12-31\n|work=FDIC Institution Directory\n|publisher=[[Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation]]\n}}</ref>\n* 1974 \u2013 acquired The Bank of Coleridge in [[Ramseur, North Carolina]] and The Bank of Commerce in [[Charlotte, North Carolina]]<ref name=\"FDIC-FCB\" />\n* 1979 \u2013 acquired Bank of Conway in [[Conway, North Carolina]]<ref name=\"FDIC-FCB\" />\n* 1981 \u2013 acquired Commercial & Farmers Bank of [[Rural Hall, North Carolina]] and Commercial & Savings Bank of [[Boonville, North Carolina]]<ref name=\"FDIC-FCB\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.firstcitizens.com/meet-first-citizens/news-awards/news/20100305-sun-american-bank/|title=First Citizens Bank Purchases Certain Assets, Assumes Certain Liabilities of Sun American Bank|date=2010-03-05|accessdate=2011-01-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110214151725/https://www.firstcitizens.com/meet-first-citizens/news-awards/news/20100305-sun-american-bank/|archive-date=2011-02-14|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.firstcitizens.com/meet-first-citizens/news-awards/news/20100129-first-regional-bank/|title=First Citizens Bank Purchases Certain Assets, Assumes Certain Liabilities of First Regional Bank|date=2010-01-29|accessdate=2011-01-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110214150213/https://www.firstcitizens.com/meet-first-citizens/news-awards/news/20100129-first-regional-bank/|archive-date=2011-02-14|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* 1983 \u2013 acquired Peoples Bank of North Carolina in [[Madison, North Carolina]]<ref name=\"FDIC-FCB\" />\n* 1985 \u2013 acquired First State Bank of [[Winterville, North Carolina]], Farmers Bank of [[Pilot Mountain, North Carolina]], and Farmers Bank of Sunbury in Sunbury, North Carolina<ref name=\"FDIC-FCB\" />\n* 1990 \u2013 acquired Heritage Federal Savings and Loan Association of [[Monroe, North Carolina]] and North Carolina Savings and Loan Association, [[Federal Association|FA]] of Charlotte, North Carolina<ref name=\"FDIC-FCB\" />\n[[File:FirstCitizensBancShares footprint.png|thumb|right|250px|First Citizens' branch footprint. From the upper left, clockwise: Florida, the North Carolina/Virginia area, southern California, and Washington state.]]\n* 1991 \u2013 acquired Mutual Savings and Loan Association of Charlotte, North Carolina and First Federal Savings Bank of [[Hendersonville, North Carolina]]<ref name=\"FDIC-FCB\" />\n* 1993 \u2013 acquired Caldwell Savings Bank of [[Lenoir, North Carolina]], Surety Federal Savings and Loan Association, FA of [[Morganton, North Carolina]], and Pioneer Savings Bank of [[Rocky Mount, North Carolina]]<ref name=\"FDIC-FCB\" />\n* 1994 \u2013 acquired The Bank of Bladenboro in [[Bladenboro, North Carolina]], Edgecomb Homestead Savings Bank of [[Tarboro, North Carolina]], and First Republic Savings Bank [[Federal savings associations|FSB]] of [[Roanoke Rapids, North Carolina]]<ref name=\"FDIC-FCB\" />\n* 1995 \u2013 acquired First Investors Savings Bank of [[Whiteville, North Carolina]] and State Bank of [[Fayetteville, North Carolina]]<ref name=\"FDIC-FCB\" />\n* 1996 \u2013 acquired First-Citizens Bank & Trust Company of [[Lawrenceville, Virginia]], Peoples Savings Bank of [[Wilmington, North Carolina]], and Summit Savings Bank of [[Sanford, North Carolina]]<ref name=\"FDIC-FCB\" />\n* 1997 \u2013 acquired First Savings Bank of Rockingham County in [[Reidsville, North Carolina]]<ref name=\"FDIC-FCB\" />\n* 1998 \u2013 acquired First Citizens Bank & Trust Company of [[White Sulphur Springs, West Virginia]]<ref name=\"FDIC-FCB\" />\n* 2003 \u2013 acquired Avery County Bank of [[Newland, North Carolina]]<ref name=\"FDIC-FCB\" />\n* 2009 \u2013 U.S. Bank National Association, a subsidiary bank of U.S. Bancorp, entered into a definitive agreement to purchase the bond trustee business of First Citizens Bank, a subsidiary of First Citizens BancShares.\n* 2009 \u2013 acquired Temecula Valley Bank<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.firstcitizens.com/meet-first-citizens/news-awards/news/20090717-temecula-valley-bank/|title=First Citizens Bank Acquires Temecula Valley Bank|date=2009-07-17|accessdate=2011-01-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110214145422/https://www.firstcitizens.com/meet-first-citizens/news-awards/news/20090717-temecula-valley-bank/|archive-date=2011-02-14|url-status=dead}}</ref> of [[Temecula, California]] and Venture Bank<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.firstcitizens.com/meet-first-citizens/news-awards/news/20090911-venture-bank/|title=First Citizens Bank Acquires Venture Bank of Washington|date=2009-09-11|accessdate=2011-01-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110214150110/https://www.firstcitizens.com/meet-first-citizens/news-awards/news/20090911-venture-bank/|archive-date=2011-02-14|url-status=dead}}</ref> of [[Lacey, Washington]]\n* 2010 \u2013 acquired First Regional Bank of [[Los Angeles, California]]<ref name=\"FDIC-FCB\" /> and Sun American Bank of [[Boca Raton, Florida]]<ref name=\"FDIC-FCB\" />\n* 2011 \u2013 changed [[Ironstone Bank]] to division from subsidiary<ref name=Ranii/>\n* 2011 \u2013 acquired United Western Bank of [[Denver, Colorado]]<ref name=United>{{cite web|url=https://www.firstcitizens.com/meet-first-citizens/news-awards/news/20110121-united-western-bank/|title=First Citizens Bank Purchases Certain Assets, Assumes Certain Liabilities Of United Western Bank|date=2011-01-21|accessdate=2011-01-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110214131218/https://www.firstcitizens.com/meet-first-citizens/news-awards/news/20110121-united-western-bank/|archive-date=2011-02-14|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* 2011 \u2013 acquired Colorado Capital Bank of [[Castle Rock, Colorado]]<ref name=Langford/>\n* 2013 \u2013 announced merger with 1st Financial Corp. of [[Hendersonville, North Carolina]]\n* 2014 \u2013 announced merger with [[First Citizens Bank of South Carolina]]\n* 2015 \u2013 acquired Capitol City Bank and Trust Company of [[Atlanta, Georgia]]<ref name=CapCity>{{cite web|title=First Citizens Bank Purchases Certain Assets, Assumes Certain Liabilities of Capitol City Bank & Trust Company of Atlanta, Ga|url=http://globenewswire.com/news-release/2015/02/13/706451/10120172/en/First-Citizens-Bank-Purchases-Certain-Assets-Assumes-Certain-Liabilities-of-Capitol-City-Bank-Trust-Company-of-Atlanta-Ga.html|accessdate=28 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Subsidiaries ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! | Name || Asset size\n|-\n| First-Citizens Bank & Trust Company\n| $18.2 billion<ref name=\"iBank\" />\n|-\n| [[Ironstone Bank]]\n| $2.8 billion<ref name=\"iBank\" />\n|}\n\n[[Image:First Citizens Bank Beaufort.jpg|250px|right|thumb|First Citizens Bank in [[Beaufort, North Carolina]]]]\n\nhttps://www.bizjournals.com/southflorida/news/2019/01/18/biscayne-bank-shareholders-approve-acquisition-by.html== References ==\n{{reflist|33em}}\nhttps://www.bizjournals.com/southflorida/news/2019/01/18/biscayne-bank-shareholders-approve-acquisition-by.html\n\n== External links ==\n{{Portal|Banks}}\n* [http://www.firstcitizens.com/ Official site]\n\n{{NASDAQ Financial-100}}\n\n[[Category:Companies based in Raleigh, North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Banks based in North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Economy of the Southeastern United States]]\n[[Category:American companies established in 1898]]\n[[Category:Banks established in 1898]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on NASDAQ]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox company\n| name           =  First Citizens BancShares\n| logo           = \n| logo_size      = 250px\n| type           = [[Public company|Public]]\n| traded_as      = {{NASDAQ|FCNCA}} (Class A)<br>[[Russell 1000 Index]] component\n| foundation     =  1898\n| location       = [[Raleigh, North Carolina]], [[United States]]\n| area_served    = [[Arizona]], [[California]], [[Colorado]], [[District of Columbia]], [[Florida]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], [[Kansas]], [[Maryland]], [[Minnesota]], [[Missouri]], [[New Mexico]], [[North Carolina]], [[Oklahoma]], [[Oregon]], [[Pennsylvania]], [[South Carolina]], [[Tennessee]], [[Texas]], [[Virginia]], [[Washington (state)|Washington]], [[West Virginia]], [[Wisconsin]] \n| key_people     = [[Frank B. Holding Jr.]] <small>([[Chief executive officer|CEO]]) ([[Chairman of the Board]])</small>\n| industry       = [[Finance]], [[Investments]], and [[Insurance]]\n| products       = [[Commercial bank]]ing, [[Investment bank]]ing\n| net_income     = {{augmentation}} [[U.S. dollar|US$]] 226 million (2016)\n| assets         =   {{augmentation}}[[U.S. dollar|US$]] 33 billion (2016)\n| num_employees  =  ~5,000\n| homepage       =  [http://www.firstcitizens.com/ www.firstcitizens.com]\n}}\n\n'''First Citizens Bancshares, Incorporated''' ({{nasdaq|FCNCA}}) is a [[bank holding company]] based in [[Raleigh, North Carolina]] that operates '''First Citizens Bank.'''  First Citizens operates in 18 states and the District of Columbia in the [[United States]], concentrated in the [[Southeastern United States]], [[Southern California]], and [[Washington (state)|Washington]].\n\nAssuming completion of a merger announced in June 2014, First Citizens Bank will become the sixth largest bank in the Southeast with 575 branches in 18 states and the [[District of Columbia]], $30.7 billion in assets, $26.1 billion in deposits, and $18 billion in loans.<ref name=SC/>  In 2010 the company employed approximately 4,400 employees.<ref name=\"iBank\">{{cite web\n|url=http://www.ibanknet.com/scripts/callreports/getbank.aspx?id=ibn1438&cert=1075612\n|title=Associated Banc-Corp\n|accessdate=2010-09-30\n|date=2010-09-30\n|work=Holding Companies\n|publisher=iBanknet.com\n}}</ref>\n\nFirst Citizens Bank serves clients in more than 200 locales with 571 branches in [[Arizona]], [[California]], [[Colorado]], [[District of Columbia]], [[Florida]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], [[Kansas]], [[Maryland]], [[Minnesota]], [[Missouri]], [[New Mexico]], [[North Carolina]], [[Oklahoma]], [[Oregon]], [[South Carolina]], [[Tennessee]], [[Texas]], [[Virginia]], [[Washington (state)|Washington]], [[Pennsylvania]], and [[West Virginia]].\n\n==History==\nIn 1998, First Citizens Bank made an agreement with [[First Citizens Bank of South Carolina]], also controlled by the Frank Holding family, allowing customers of either bank to conduct transactions with the other institution.<ref>\"Briefly,\" ''The News & Observer'', July 23, 1998, p. D2.</ref>\n\nDec 22, 2003, Citizens Bancshares restated its previously announced 2003 third quarter earnings, following a determination by its independent auditors to change its accounting treatment of one third quarter transaction related to shares of the Company's common stock donated to it by an unrelated third party.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/containers/fix031/813640/000110465903029082/a03-6490_1ex99d1.htm| title=Citizens Bancshares Corporation Announces Revised Third Quarter Earnings}}</ref>\n\nOn October 8, 2010, First Citizens filed a merger application with federal regulators, the [[Office of the Comptroller of the Currency]] and the [[Federal Reserve Bank of Richmond]], and respective state banking departments in IronStone's footprint. IronStone Bank will continue to operate under its trade name.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/charlotte/stories/2010/10/04/daily54.html|title=\nFirst Citizens looks to merge with IronStone Bank|last=Weisbecker|first=Lee|work=[[Charlotte Business Journal]]|date=2010-10-08|accessdate=2011-01-24}}</ref> The change became official January 7, 2011.<ref name=Ranii>{{cite news|url=http://blogs.newsobserver.com/business/first-citizens-completes-in-house-merger|title=First Citizens completes in-house merger|last=Ranii|first=David|work=[[News & Observer]]|date=2011-01-07|accessdate=2011-01-07}}</ref>\n\nFirst Citizens Bank entered into an agreement with the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. (FDIC) to purchase substantially all the assets and assume the majority of the liabilities of United Western Bank, [[Denver, Colorado]] on January 21, 2011.<ref name=United/> Months later First Citizens took over the failed Colorado Capital Bank of [[Castle Rock, Colorado]] in a similar deal. It was the sixth FDIC-related agreement since July 2009.<ref name=Langford>{{cite news|url=http://www.salisburypost.com/News/071711-biz-roundup-langford-nominee-qcd|title=Lighting company CFO finalist for honor|work=[[Salisbury Post]]|date=2011-01-21|accessdate=2011-01-24|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110924031733/http://www.salisburypost.com/News/071711-biz-roundup-langford-nominee-qcd|archivedate=2011-09-24}}</ref> First Citizens now has 14 branches in Colorado, 3 of them IronStone.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/First-Citizens-Bank-Purchases-pz-416410419.html?x=0&.v=1|title=First Citizens Bank Purchases Certain Assets, Assumes Certain Liabilities of Colorado Capital Bank|work=Yahoo Finance|date=2011-07-08|accessdate=2011-07-21}}</ref>\n\nOn December 10, 2013, 1st Financial Corp. shareholders approved a merger with First Citizens. As of September 30, 2013, [[Hendersonville, North Carolina]]-based 1st Financial had 12 branches in Western North Carolina, $675 million in assets and $660 million in deposits. In spring 2014, accounts of Mountain 1st Bank & Trust are to change to First Citizens.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.citizen-times.com/article/20131211/NEWS/312110049/Mountain-1st-First-Citizens-merger-OK-d|title=Mountain 1st-First Citizens merger OK'd|work=[[Asheville Citizen-Times]]|date=2013-12-10|accessdate=2013-12-18}}</ref>\n\nOn October 1, 2014, First Citizens completed a merger with [[First Citizens Bank of South Carolina]], making First Citizens the sixth-largest bank in the Southeast resulting in the largest bank in the United States controlled by a single family. First Citizens had no branches in South Carolina before the merger, while First Citizens and the South Carolina-based bank both had branches in Georgia.<ref name=SC>{{cite news|url=http://www.thestate.com/2014/06/11/3501235/first-citizens-bank-buys-sc-based.html|title=First Citizens Bank buys SC-based bank|last=Ranii|first=David|work=[[News & Observer]]|date=2014-06-11|accessdate=2014-06-11|archive-url=https://archive.is/20140611151752/http://www.thestate.com/2014/06/11/3501235/first-citizens-bank-buys-sc-based.html|archive-date=2014-06-11|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=First Citizens Completes Merger|work=[[Asheville Citizen-Times]]|date=2014-10-05|page=E2}}</ref>\n\nOn March 11, 2016, North Milwaukee State Bank of [[Milwaukee]], the first bank to fail in 2016, was taken over and the FDIC appointed receiver. First Citizens agreed to purchase most of the $67.1 million in assets and all of the deposits.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.newsobserver.com/news/business/article65953337.html|title=First Citizens acquires failed Wisconsin bank|last=Ranii|first=David|work=News & Observer|date=2016-03-14|accessdate=2016-05-09}}</ref>\n\nOn May 6, 2016, First Citizens announced the purchase of [[King of Prussia, Pennsylvania]]-based First CornerStone Bank, the third financial institution to fail in 2016, with six branches, $103.3 million in assets and $101 million in deposits.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.newsobserver.com/news/business/article76492917.html|title=First Citizens Bank acquires failed Pa. bank |last=Ranii|first=David|work=News & Observer|date=2016-05-09|accessdate=2016-05-09}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2016, First Citizens completed its $35 million purchase of Cordia Bancorp Inc. of [[Midlothian, Virginia]], with $353.8 million in assets.<ref name=Journal/>\n\nOn January 13, 2017, First Citizens announced it agreed to take over the failed Harvest Community Bank of [[Pennsville, New Jersey]], with $126.4 million in assets and four branches.<ref name=Journal>{{cite news|url=http://www.journalnow.com/business/business_news/local/the-briefcase-local-businessmen-offer-securities-for-sneez/article_7ab36c0d-b2ce-50b1-91da-ba8063d9de3c.html|title=The Briefcase: Local businessmen offer securities for SneeZ|work=[[Winston-Salem Journal]]|date=2017-01-16|accessdate=2017-02-02}}</ref>\n\nOn May 5, 2017, First Citizens announced it agreed to take over the failed Milwaukee-based Guaranty Bank of [[Milwaukee, Wisconsin]], with estimated $1 billion in assets.<ref name=Fox6>{{cite news|url=http://fox6now.com/2017/05/05/federal-agency-shuts-down-all-guaranty-bank-branches-will-be-absorbed-by-first-citizens-bank/|title=Federal agency shuts down number of Guaranty Bank branches; some to reopen as First-Citizens Bank|work=[[Fox 6 News]]|date=2017-05-05|accessdate=2017-05-06}}</ref>\n\n== Timeline ==\nFirst Citizens Bank, first known as the Bank of [[Smithfield, North Carolina|Smithfield]], opened on March 1, 1898. It eventually evolved into First National Bank of Smithfield, and merged with Citizens National Bank to become First and Citizens National Bank. In 1929, it changed its name to First-Citizens Bank and Trust Company.<ref name=Holding>[https://www.ncdcr.gov/blog/2015/03/01/the-holding-family-and-first-citizens-bank The Holding Family and First Citizens Bank] at [[North Carolina Department of Natural Resources.</ref> It reorganized as a holding company, First Citizens BancShares, in 1986.<ref>[https://last10k.com/sec-filings/report/798941/000079894118000006/fcnca_10kx12312017.htm 2017 Form 10-K]</ref> \n\nFor three generations, the bank has been led by the family of Robert Powell Holding, who joined the bank in 1918 and rose to president in 1935.<ref name=Holding/>\n\n* 1971 \u2013 acquired The Haynes Bank of Cliffside, North Carolina<ref name=\"FDIC-FCB\">{{cite web\n|url=http://www2.fdic.gov/idasp/report_bhc.asp?inSortIndex=0&inCert1=1075612&period1=06/30/2006\n|title=Bank Holding Company Detail\n|accessdate=2007-04-15\n|date=2006-12-31\n|work=FDIC Institution Directory\n|publisher=[[Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation]]\n}}</ref>\n* 1974 \u2013 acquired The Bank of Coleridge in [[Ramseur, North Carolina]] and The Bank of Commerce in [[Charlotte, North Carolina]]<ref name=\"FDIC-FCB\" />\n* 1979 \u2013 acquired Bank of Conway in [[Conway, North Carolina]]<ref name=\"FDIC-FCB\" />\n* 1981 \u2013 acquired Commercial & Farmers Bank of [[Rural Hall, North Carolina]] and Commercial & Savings Bank of [[Boonville, North Carolina]]<ref name=\"FDIC-FCB\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.firstcitizens.com/meet-first-citizens/news-awards/news/20100305-sun-american-bank/|title=First Citizens Bank Purchases Certain Assets, Assumes Certain Liabilities of Sun American Bank|date=2010-03-05|accessdate=2011-01-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110214151725/https://www.firstcitizens.com/meet-first-citizens/news-awards/news/20100305-sun-american-bank/|archive-date=2011-02-14|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.firstcitizens.com/meet-first-citizens/news-awards/news/20100129-first-regional-bank/|title=First Citizens Bank Purchases Certain Assets, Assumes Certain Liabilities of First Regional Bank|date=2010-01-29|accessdate=2011-01-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110214150213/https://www.firstcitizens.com/meet-first-citizens/news-awards/news/20100129-first-regional-bank/|archive-date=2011-02-14|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* 1983 \u2013 acquired Peoples Bank of North Carolina in [[Madison, North Carolina]]<ref name=\"FDIC-FCB\" />\n* 1985 \u2013 acquired First State Bank of [[Winterville, North Carolina]], Farmers Bank of [[Pilot Mountain, North Carolina]], and Farmers Bank of Sunbury in Sunbury, North Carolina<ref name=\"FDIC-FCB\" />\n* 1990 \u2013 acquired Heritage Federal Savings and Loan Association of [[Monroe, North Carolina]] and North Carolina Savings and Loan Association, [[Federal Association|FA]] of Charlotte, North Carolina<ref name=\"FDIC-FCB\" />\n[[File:FirstCitizensBancShares footprint.png|thumb|right|250px|First Citizens' branch footprint. From the upper left, clockwise: Florida, the North Carolina/Virginia area, southern California, and Washington state.]]\n* 1991 \u2013 acquired Mutual Savings and Loan Association of Charlotte, North Carolina and First Federal Savings Bank of [[Hendersonville, North Carolina]]<ref name=\"FDIC-FCB\" />\n* 1993 \u2013 acquired Caldwell Savings Bank of [[Lenoir, North Carolina]], Surety Federal Savings and Loan Association, FA of [[Morganton, North Carolina]], and Pioneer Savings Bank of [[Rocky Mount, North Carolina]]<ref name=\"FDIC-FCB\" />\n* 1994 \u2013 acquired The Bank of Bladenboro in [[Bladenboro, North Carolina]], Edgecomb Homestead Savings Bank of [[Tarboro, North Carolina]], and First Republic Savings Bank [[Federal savings associations|FSB]] of [[Roanoke Rapids, North Carolina]]<ref name=\"FDIC-FCB\" />\n* 1995 \u2013 acquired First Investors Savings Bank of [[Whiteville, North Carolina]] and State Bank of [[Fayetteville, North Carolina]]<ref name=\"FDIC-FCB\" />\n* 1996 \u2013 acquired First-Citizens Bank & Trust Company of [[Lawrenceville, Virginia]], Peoples Savings Bank of [[Wilmington, North Carolina]], and Summit Savings Bank of [[Sanford, North Carolina]]<ref name=\"FDIC-FCB\" />\n* 1997 \u2013 acquired First Savings Bank of Rockingham County in [[Reidsville, North Carolina]]<ref name=\"FDIC-FCB\" />\n* 1998 \u2013 acquired First Citizens Bank & Trust Company of [[White Sulphur Springs, West Virginia]]<ref name=\"FDIC-FCB\" />\n* 2003 \u2013 acquired Avery County Bank of [[Newland, North Carolina]]<ref name=\"FDIC-FCB\" />\n* 2009 \u2013 U.S. Bank National Association, a subsidiary bank of U.S. Bancorp, entered into a definitive agreement to purchase the bond trustee business of First Citizens Bank, a subsidiary of First Citizens BancShares.\n* 2009 \u2013 acquired Temecula Valley Bank<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.firstcitizens.com/meet-first-citizens/news-awards/news/20090717-temecula-valley-bank/|title=First Citizens Bank Acquires Temecula Valley Bank|date=2009-07-17|accessdate=2011-01-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110214145422/https://www.firstcitizens.com/meet-first-citizens/news-awards/news/20090717-temecula-valley-bank/|archive-date=2011-02-14|url-status=dead}}</ref> of [[Temecula, California]] and Venture Bank<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.firstcitizens.com/meet-first-citizens/news-awards/news/20090911-venture-bank/|title=First Citizens Bank Acquires Venture Bank of Washington|date=2009-09-11|accessdate=2011-01-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110214150110/https://www.firstcitizens.com/meet-first-citizens/news-awards/news/20090911-venture-bank/|archive-date=2011-02-14|url-status=dead}}</ref> of [[Lacey, Washington]]\n* 2010 \u2013 acquired First Regional Bank of [[Los Angeles, California]]<ref name=\"FDIC-FCB\" /> and Sun American Bank of [[Boca Raton, Florida]]<ref name=\"FDIC-FCB\" />\n* 2011 \u2013 changed [[Ironstone Bank]] to division from subsidiary<ref name=Ranii/>\n* 2011 \u2013 acquired United Western Bank of [[Denver, Colorado]]<ref name=United>{{cite web|url=https://www.firstcitizens.com/meet-first-citizens/news-awards/news/20110121-united-western-bank/|title=First Citizens Bank Purchases Certain Assets, Assumes Certain Liabilities Of United Western Bank|date=2011-01-21|accessdate=2011-01-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110214131218/https://www.firstcitizens.com/meet-first-citizens/news-awards/news/20110121-united-western-bank/|archive-date=2011-02-14|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* 2011 \u2013 acquired Colorado Capital Bank of [[Castle Rock, Colorado]]<ref name=Langford/>\n* 2013 \u2013 announced merger with 1st Financial Corp. of [[Hendersonville, North Carolina]]\n* 2014 \u2013 announced merger with [[First Citizens Bank of South Carolina]]\n* 2015 \u2013 acquired Capitol City Bank and Trust Company of [[Atlanta, Georgia]]<ref name=CapCity>{{cite web|title=First Citizens Bank Purchases Certain Assets, Assumes Certain Liabilities of Capitol City Bank & Trust Company of Atlanta, Ga|url=http://globenewswire.com/news-release/2015/02/13/706451/10120172/en/First-Citizens-Bank-Purchases-Certain-Assets-Assumes-Certain-Liabilities-of-Capitol-City-Bank-Trust-Company-of-Atlanta-Ga.html|accessdate=28 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Subsidiaries ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! | Name || Asset size\n|-\n| First-Citizens Bank & Trust Company\n| $18.2 billion<ref name=\"iBank\" />\n|-\n| [[Ironstone Bank]]\n| $2.8 billion<ref name=\"iBank\" />\n|}\n\n[[Image:First Citizens Bank Beaufort.jpg|250px|right|thumb|First Citizens Bank in [[Beaufort, North Carolina]]]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|33em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Portal|Banks}}\n* [http://www.firstcitizens.com/ Official site]\n\n{{NASDAQ Financial-100}}\n\n[[Category:Companies based in Raleigh, North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Banks based in North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Economy of the Southeastern United States]]\n[[Category:American companies established in 1898]]\n[[Category:Banks established in 1898]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on NASDAQ]]\n", "name_user": "Darkhorse0102", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/First_Citizens_BancShares"}
